## Why This Is Asked
Tests the ability to combine hash tables with heaps for real-time top-K queries under sliding-window expirations. It evaluates understanding of lazy cleanup techniques, time-based eviction strategies, and maintaining data consistency under concurrent updates.

## Key Concepts
- Hash map for O(1) task lookups and metadata storage
- Max-heap for efficient top-K ordering
- Lazy deletion to avoid expensive per-update heap removals
- Time-based expiration using timestamp validation

## Code Example
```javascript
class Leaderboard {
  constructor(W) {
    this.W = W;
    this.map = new Map(); // task_id -> {score, timestamp}
    this.heap = new MaxHeap(); // (score, task_id)
  }

  update(task_id, delta, ts) {
    const current = this.map.get(task_id) || { score: 0, timestamp: 0 };
    const updated = { 
      score: current.score + delta, 
      timestamp: ts 
    };
    this.map.set(task_id, updated);
    this.heap.push([updated.score, task_id]);
  }

  getTopK(k, current_ts) {
    const result = [];
    const temp = [];

    while (result.length < k && !this.heap.isEmpty()) {
      const [score, task_id] = this.heap.pop();
      const task = this.map.get(task_id);

      if (task && task.score === score && current_ts - task.timestamp <= this.W) {
        result.push({ task_id, score });
      } else {
        temp.push([score, task_id]);
      }
    }

    // Restore invalid entries
    temp.forEach(entry => this.heap.push(entry));

    return result;
  }
}
```

## Complexity Analysis
- **Update**: O(1) hash map + O(log n) heap push = O(log n)
- **Top-K query**: O(k log n) worst case due to lazy deletion
- **Space**: O(n) for hash map + heap (potentially O(n + m) where m are stale entries)
- **Expiration**: Handled during queries via timestamp validation

