## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design streaming state with sliding windows, using hash maps, per-id deques (linked lists), and a heap for ranking. Emphasizes correctness under out-of-order arrivals and lazy expirations.

## Key Concepts
- Sliding-window maintenance per key using a deque
- Lazy expiration and lazy heap invalidation
- Top-K extraction via a max-heap with versioning

## Code Example
```javascript
class RealTimeTopKWindow {
  constructor(W) {
    this.W = W;
    this.byId = new Map(); // id -> { deque: [], sum, version }
    this.globalMax = new MinHeap((a,b)=>b.sum-a.sum); // max-heap emulation
  }
  addEvent(id, value, ts) {
    // Ensure id exists
    const rec = this.byId.get(id) || { deque: [], sum: 0, version: 0 };
    // expire old
    while (rec.deque.length && rec.deque[0].ts <= ts - this.W) {
      const old = rec.deque.shift();
      rec.sum -= old.value;
    }
    rec.deque.push({ ts, value });
    rec.sum += value;
    rec.version++;
    this.byId.set(id, rec);
    this.globalMax.push({ sum: rec.sum, id, ver: rec.version });
  }
  getTopK(K) {
    const res = [];
    const seen = new Set();
    while (res.length < K) {
      const top = this.globalMax.pop();
      if (!top) break;
      const cur = this.byId.get(top.id);
      if (!cur || cur.version !== top.ver || top.sum !== cur.sum) continue; // stale
      if (!seen.has(top.id)) {
        res.push(top.id);
        seen.add(top.id);
      }
    }
    return res;
  }
}
```

