## Concept Overview
An LRU (Least Recently Used) cache efficiently manages memory by evicting the least accessed items when capacity is reached. This implementation leverages a HashMap for fast key lookups and a DoublyLinkedList for maintaining access order.

## Implementation Details
- **HashMap**: Maps keys to Node references, enabling O(1) lookup operations
- **DoublyLinkedList**: Maintains access order with head representing most recently used items and tail representing least recently used items
- **Thread Safety**: ReentrantReadWriteLock provides optimal concurrency - multiple threads can read simultaneously while writes are mutually exclusive
- **Eviction Policy**: When capacity is exceeded, the tail node (least recently used) is removed
- **Operations**: Both get() and put() operations maintain O(1) time complexity

## Code Example
```java
public class LRUCache<K, V> {
    private final Map<K, Node<K, V>> cache;
    private final DoublyLinkedList<K, V> order;
    private final ReentrantReadWriteLock lock;
    private final int capacity;

    public LRUCache(int capacity) {
        this.capacity = capacity;
        this.cache = new HashMap<>();
        this.order = new DoublyLinkedList<>();
        this.lock = new ReentrantReadWriteLock();
    }

    public V get(K key) {
        lock.readLock().lock();
        try {
            Node<K, V> node = cache.get(key);
            if (node != null) {
                // Upgrade to write lock for reordering
                lock.readLock().unlock();
                lock.writeLock().lock();
                order.moveToHead(node);
                return node.value;
            }
            return null;
        } finally {
            if (lock.isWriteLocked()) {
                lock.writeLock().unlock();
            } else {
                lock.readLock().unlock();
            }
        }
    }

    public void put(K key, V value) {
        lock.writeLock().lock();
        try {
            Node<K, V> existing = cache.get(key);
            if (existing != null) {
                existing.value = value;
                order.moveToHead(existing);
                return;
            }

            Node<K, V> newNode = new Node<>(key, value);
            cache.put(key, newNode);
            order.addToHead(newNode);

            if (cache.size() > capacity) {
                Node<K, V> tail = order.removeTail();
                cache.remove(tail.key);
            }
        } finally {
            lock.writeLock().unlock();
        }
    }
}```

