## Key Concepts

1. **Sliding window per user** — Each user maintains their own event history, allowing O(1) expiration of old events via queue front-draining.
2. **Lazy invalidation** — The heap never explicitly deletes stale entries; instead, we check and skip them during retrieval. This keeps `addEvent` at O(log n) without expensive heap repairs.
3. **Aggregate maps** — Fast O(1) lookup and update of per-user totals, avoiding full recalculation.
4. **Tie-breaking** — Using `(delta, user_id)` as a composite key ensures stable, deterministic ordering.

## Code Example

```javascript
class RollingActiveUsers {
  constructor(windowSeconds) {
    this.W = windowSeconds;
    this.userWindows = new Map();
    this.userTotals = new Map();
    this.maxHeap = new MaxHeap();
  }

  addEvent(ts, userId, delta) {
    if (!this.userWindows.has(userId)) {
      this.userWindows.set(userId, []);
      this.userTotals.set(userId, 0);
    }
    this.userWindows.get(userId).push({ ts, delta });
    const newTotal = this.userTotals.get(userId) + delta;
    this.userTotals.set(userId, newTotal);
    this.maxHeap.push({ delta: newTotal, userId });
    this.expireIfNeeded(userId, ts);
  }

  expireIfNeeded(userId, now) {
    const cutoff = now - this.W;
    const events = this.userWindows.get(userId);
    while (events.length && events[0].ts < cutoff) {
      const expired = events.shift();
      this.userTotals.set(userId, this.userTotals.get(userId) - expired.delta);
    }
  }

  topKUsers(k, now) {
    const results = [];
    for (let i = 0; i < k; i++) {
      const top = this.maxHeap.pop();
      if (!top || !this.isValid(top, now)) break;
      results.push(top.userId);
      this.maxHeap.push(top);
    }
    return results;
  }

  isValid(entry, now) {
    const currentTotal = this.userTotals.get(entry.userId);
    return currentTotal !== undefined && Math.abs(currentTotal - entry.delta) < 0.0001;
  }
}
```

