## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to design a DP over partitions using prefix sums and a hashmap to achieve linear-time partition counting. This also exercises both bottom-up and top-down reasoning, and edge-case handling for K and negative numbers.

## Key Concepts

- Prefix sums
- Hash map DP
- Edge-case handling (K=0, negative numbers)

## Code Example

```javascript
function countPartitions(A, K) {
  const MOD = 1000000007;
  const N = A.length;
  const prefix = new Array(N+1).fill(0);
  for (let i = 1; i <= N; i++) prefix[i] = prefix[i-1] + A[i-1];
  const dp = new Array(N+1).fill(0);
  dp[0] = 1;
  const map = new Map();
  map.set(0, 1);
  for (let i = 1; i <= N; i++) {
    const key = prefix[i] - K;
    const ways = map.get(key) ?? 0;
    dp[i] = ways;
    const cur = (map.get(prefix[i]) ?? 0) + dp[i];
    map.set(prefix[i], cur % MOD);
  }
  return dp[N] % MOD;
}
``` 

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you adapt to count partitions with an additional constraint, e.g., every block length <= L?
- What if A contains large numbers and K is dynamic per query?

questions.answer:
## Problem: Deadline-Constrained Task Scheduling

Given N tasks where each task i has:
- Duration `t[i]` (time needed to complete)
- Deadline `d[i]` (must finish by this time)
- Value `v[i]` (benefit earned)

Schedule tasks on a single machine starting at time 0 to maximize total value. Each task can be taken at most once, in any order. Return the maximum value and one valid sequence.

---

## Solution 1: Top-Down Memoized DP

**Key insight**: Sort by deadline, then use recursion with memoization where state `(i, time)` tracks the current time position.

```javascript
function maxValueTopDown(tasks) {
  // Sort by deadline to ensure feasibility constraints are checked correctly
  tasks.sort((a, b) => a.d - b.d);
  const n = tasks.length;
  if (n === 0) return { maxValue: 0, sequence: [] };

  const maxTime = Math.max(...tasks.map(t => t.d));
  const memo = new Map();
  // Track decisions for reconstruction: 'take' | 'skip' | null
  const decision = Array.from({ length: n }, () => new Array(maxTime + 1).fill(null));

  function dfs(i, time) {
    // Base case: no more tasks to consider
    if (i === n) return 0;

    // Pruning: exceeded all deadlines
    if (time > maxTime) return Number.NEGATIVE_INFINITY;

    const key = `${i},${time}`;
    if (memo.has(key)) return memo.get(key);

    // Option 1: Skip current task
    let best = dfs(i + 1, time);
    decision[i][time] = 'skip';

    // Option 2: Take current task (if feasible)
    const task = tasks[i];
    if (time + task.t <= task.d) {
      const take = task.v + dfs(i + 1, time + task.t);
      if (take > best) {
        best = take;
        decision[i][time] = 'take';
      }
    }

    memo.set(key, best);
    return best;
  }

  function reconstruct() {
    const seq = [];
    let i = 0, time = 0;
    while (i < n) {
      if (decision[i][time] === 'take') {
        seq.push(i); // Store original index
        time += tasks[i].t;
      }
      i++;
    }
    return seq;
  }

  const maxVal = dfs(0, 0);
  // Handle case where no feasible schedule exists
  if (maxVal === Number.NEGATIVE_INFINITY) {
    return { maxValue: 0, sequence: [] };
  }

  return { maxValue: maxVal, sequence: reconstruct() };
}
```

---

## Solution 2: Bottom-Up Tabulation

```javascript
function maxValueBottomUp(tasks) {
  tasks.sort((a, b) => a.d - b.d);
  const n = tasks.length;
  if (n === 0) return { maxValue: 0, sequence: [] };

  const maxTime = Math.max(...tasks.map(t => t.d));

  // dp[i][t] = max value considering first i tasks, ending at time t
  const dp = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => new Array(maxTime + 1).fill(0));
  // parent[i][t] = { taken: boolean, prevT: number } for reconstruction
  const parent = Array.from({ length: n + 1 }, () => 
    new Array(maxTime + 1).fill(null)
  );

  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    const task = tasks[i - 1];
    for (let t = 0; t <= maxTime; t++) {
      // Start with skipping the task
      dp[i][t] = dp[i - 1][t];
      parent[i][t] = { taken: false, prevT: t };

      // Consider taking: can only finish at t if task ends by deadline
      if (t >= task.t && t <= task.d) {
        const candidate = dp[i - 1][t - task.t] + task.v;
        if (candidate > dp[i][t]) {
          dp[i][t] = candidate;
          parent[i][t] = { taken: true, prevT: t - task.t };
        }
      }
    }
  }

  // Find time t with maximum value
  let bestT = 0;
  for (let t = 0; t <= maxTime; t++) {
    if (dp[n][t] > dp[n][bestT]) bestT = t;
  }

  function reconstruct() {
    const seq = [];
    let i = n, t = bestT;
    while (i > 0) {
      const p = parent[i][t];
      if (p.taken) {
        seq.unshift(i - 1); // Store original index
      }
      t = p.prevT;
      i--;
    }
    return seq;
  }

  return { maxValue: dp[n][bestT], sequence: reconstruct() };
}
```

---

## Edge Cases

| Scenario | Handling |
|----------|----------|
| **No feasible schedule** | Both solutions return `{ maxValue: 0, sequence: [] }` |
| **Task finishes exactly at deadline** | Valid; uses `<=` in feasibility check |
| **Tight deadlines** | DP correctly prunes infeasible states |
| **Multiple optimal solutions** | Returns one valid optimal schedule |
| **Empty input** | Returns `{ maxValue: 0, sequence: [] }` immediately |
| **Tasks with same deadline** | Sort is stable; any valid ordering works |
| **Single task** | Works; returns it if feasible, else empty |

---

## Complexity Analysis

| Approach | Time | Space |
|----------|------|-------|
| Top-down | O(n × D) | O(n × D) |
| Bottom-up | O(n × D) | O(n × D) |

Where `D = max deadline`. Space can be reduced to O(D) for bottom-up using rolling arrays.

questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked
This problem validates DP mastery (two implementations) and handling of substring lookups with a dictionary. It stresses practical constraints and edge-case handling.

## Key Concepts
- Bottom-up DP, Memoization, Time: O(N * maxLen)
- Hash-map lookups for dictionary scores
- Edge cases: no decomposition, empty input, overlapping choices

## Code Example
```javascript
// Bottom-up
function maxScore(s, dict) {
  const maxLen = Math.max(...Object.keys(dict).map(k => k.length));
  const n = s.length;
  const NEG = -1e15;
  const dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(NEG);
  dp[0] = 0;
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    for (let len = 1; len <= Math.min(i, maxLen); len++) {
      const substr = s.slice(i - len, i);
      if (dict.hasOwnProperty(substr) && dp[i - len] !== NEG) {
        dp[i] = Math.max(dp[i], dp[i - len] + dict[substr]);
      }
    }
  }
  return dp[n] === NEG ? -1 : dp[n];
}

// Top-down
function maxScoreTopDown(s, dict) {
  const maxLen = Math.max(...Object.keys(dict).map(k => k.length));
  const memo = new Map();
  function solve(i) {
    if (i === s.length) return 0;
    if (memo.has(i)) return memo.get(i);
    let best = -Infinity;
    for (let len = 1; len <= Math.min(maxLen, s.length - i); len++) {
      const substr = s.substring(i, i + len);
      if (dict.hasOwnProperty(substr)) {
        const val = dict[substr] + solve(i + len);
        if (val > best) best = val;
      }
    }
    memo.set(i, best);
    return best;
  }
  const res = solve(0);
  return res === -Infinity ? -1 : res;
}
``` 

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you adapt it if dictionary lookups are expensive and you need pruning?
- How would you extend to handle negative scores or required minimum total?

## Why This Is Asked

This question evaluates dynamic programming skills with state expansion, requiring candidates to track whether the cell removal has been used. It tests proper handling of grid boundary conditions and provides opportunities to discuss space optimization strategies and compare memoization versus tabulation approaches.

## Key Concepts
- DP with auxiliary state tracking
- Space optimization using rolling arrays
- Boundary condition handling
- State transition logic

## Code Example
```javascript
function minPathWithOneRemoval(grid) {
  const m = grid.length, n = grid[0].length;
  const dp0 = Array(m).fill().map(() => Array(n).fill(Infinity));
  const dp1 = Array(m).fill().map(() => Array(n).fill(Infinity));

  dp0[0][0] = grid[0][0];
  dp1[0][0] = 0;

  for (let i = 0; i < m; i++) {
    for (let j = 0; j < n; j++) {
      if (i > 0) {
        dp0[i][j] = Math.min(dp0[i][j], grid[i][j] + dp0[i-1][j]);
        dp1[i][j] = Math.min(dp1[i][j], grid[i][j] + dp1[i-1][j]);
        dp1[i][j] = Math.min(dp1[i][j], dp0[i-1][j]);
      }
      if (j > 0) {
        dp0[i][j] = Math.min(dp0[i][j], grid[i][j] + dp0[i][j-1]);
        dp1[i][j] = Math.min(dp1[i][j], grid[i][j] + dp1[i][j-1]);
        dp1[i][j] = Math.min(dp1[i][j], dp0[i][j-1]);
      }
    }
  }

  return Math.min(dp0[m-1][n-1], dp1[m-1][n-1]);
}
```

## Time/Space Complexity
- Time: O(m × n) - we process each cell once
- Space: O(m × n) - can be optimized to O(n) using rolling arrays since we only need the previous row

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to formalize DP for partitioning into constrained blocks and compare top-down vs bottom-up implementations with proper modulo handling.

## Key Concepts
- Top-down memoization with pruning
- Bottom-up tabulation
- Positive number optimization
- Modulo arithmetic and edge cases

## Code Example
```javascript
// Top-down memoized solution
function countPartitions(nums, target) {
  const n = nums.length;
  const memo = new Array(n+1).fill(-1);
  const MOD = 1_000_000_007;

  function dfs(i) {
    if (i === n) return 1;
    if (memo[i] !== -1) return memo[i];

    let sum = 0, ways = 0;
    for (let j = i; j < n; j++) {
      sum += nums[j];
      if (sum > target) break;
      if (sum === target) {
        ways = (ways + dfs(j + 1)) % MOD;
      }
    }
    return memo[i] = ways;
  }

  return dfs(0);
}

// Bottom-up tabulation sketch
function countPartitionsBottomUp(nums, target) {
  const n = nums.length;
  const dp = new Array(n+1).fill(0);
  dp[0] = 1;

  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    let sum = 0;
    for (let j = i; j < n && sum + nums[j] <= target; j++) {
      sum += nums[j];
      if (sum === target) {
        dp[j+1] = (dp[j+1] + dp[i]) % MOD;
      }
    }
  }
  return dp[n];
}
```

## Edge Cases
- Empty input: return 0
- Large target: handle with modulo and pruning
- Single element equal to target: return 1
- No valid partition: return 0

## Correctness Justification
Top-down explores all valid partitions by recursively trying all possible block endings. Memoization avoids recomputation. Bottom-up builds from base case, accumulating ways to reach each position. Both respect positive numbers enabling early termination when sum exceeds target.

