questions.explanation:
## Why This Is Asked
This question assesses dynamic programming fundamentals through practical string segmentation, testing understanding of both top-down memoization and bottom-up tabulation approaches.

## Key Concepts
- Dynamic Programming: memoization vs. tabulation
- String matching optimization (startsWith, trie)
- Time and space trade-offs between DP approaches
- State definition and transition logic

## Code Example
```javascript
// Top-down memoized solution
function minWordSegmentsTopDown(s, dict) {
  const n = s.length;
  const memo = Array(n + 1).fill(-1);
  memo[n] = 0;

  function dfs(i) {
    if (memo[i] !== -1) return memo[i];
    let minSegs = Infinity;
    for (const word of dict) {
      if (s.startsWith(word, i)) {
        const result = dfs(i + word.length);
        if (result !== -1) {
          minSegs = Math.min(minSegs, 1 + result);
        }
      }
    }
    memo[i] = minSegs === Infinity ? -1 : minSegs;
    return memo[i];
  }
  return dfs(0);
}

// Bottom-up tabulated solution
function minWordSegmentsBottomUp(s, dict) {
  const n = s.length;
  const dp = Array(n + 1).fill(Infinity);
  dp[n] = 0;

  for (let i = n - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
    for (const word of dict) {
      if (s.startsWith(word, i)) {
        if (dp[i + word.length] !== Infinity) {
          dp[i] = Math.min(dp[i], 1 + dp[i + word.length]);
        }
      }
    }
  }
  return dp[0] === Infinity ? -1 : dp[0];
}
```

## Complexity Analysis
- **Time:** O(n × m × L) where n = |s|, m = dict size, L = avg word length. Using a Trie reduces this to O(n × L).
- **Space:** O(n) for the memo/DP array.

## Why This Question Is Asked
This question tests dynamic programming intuition on a constrained path counting problem with simple transitions and boundary conditions.

## Key Concepts
- **Recurrence relation:** f(i) = f(i+1) + f(i+2) with modulo arithmetic
- **Memoization vs. tabulation:** Trade-offs between recursive top-down with caching versus iterative bottom-up approaches
- **Edge conditions:** Blocked start/end positions, single-cell arrays

## Code Example
```javascript
function countPaths(blocked) {
  const n = blocked.length;
  const MOD = 1000000007;
  if (blocked[0]) return 0;

  // Memoized DFS
  const memo = Array(n).fill(-1);
  function dfs(i) {
    if (i === n - 1) return blocked[i] ? 0 : 1;
    if (i >= n || blocked[i]) return 0;
    if (memo[i] !== -1) return memo[i];
    memo[i] = (dfs(i + 1) + dfs(i + 2)) % MOD;
    return memo[i];
  }
  return dfs(0);
}

// Bottom-up DP (O(1) space)
function countPathsDP(blocked) {
  const n = blocked.length;
  const MOD = 1000000007;
  if (blocked[0]) return 0;

  let next2 = 1, next1 = blocked[n - 1] ? 0 : 1;
  for (let i = n - 2; i >= 0; i--) {
    const curr = blocked[i] ? 0 : (next1 + next2) % MOD;
    next2 = next1;
    next1 = curr;
  }
  return next1;
}
```

## Why This Is Asked

Tests ability to model DP with obstacles and variable step sizes, requiring careful base cases and transition logic. It also assesses both memoization and tabulation familiarity.

## Key Concepts

- DP with multiple transitions (1..k)
- Handling blocked steps
- Memoization vs tabulation
- Time complexity: O(n*maxJump); Space: O(n) (or O(maxJump) with optimization)

## Code Example

```javascript
// Bottom-up tabulation
function countWays(n, maxJump, blocked) {
  const dp = new Array(n + 1).fill(0);
  dp[0] = 1;
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    if (blocked[i]) { dp[i] = 0; continue; }
    for (let j = 1; j <= maxJump; j++) {
      if (i - j >= 0) dp[i] += dp[i - j];
    }
  }
  return dp[n];
}
```

```javascript
// Memoized recursive version
function countWaysRec(n, maxJump, blocked, i = n, memo = {}) {
  if (i === 0) return 1;
  if (i < 0 || blocked[i]) return 0;
  if (memo[i] !== undefined) return memo[i];
  let ways = 0;
  for (let t = 1; t <= maxJump; t++) ways += countWaysRec(n, maxJump, blocked, i - t, memo);
  memo[i] = ways;
  return ways;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions

- How would you optimize to O(maxJump) space with a sliding window?
- How would you adjust for modulo arithmetic to prevent overflow for large n?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests ability to design a DP with variable-length segments and per-segment value, plus both memoized and tabulated solutions.

## Key Concepts
- Dynamic programming over positions with limited jump length
- Maintaining per-iteration maximums within a window
