To compute shortest distances from a source node s to all other nodes in a directed graph with non-negative weighted edges, we can use a topological-order DP approach when the graph is acyclic:

1. Build adjacency list and indegree arrays
2. Perform Kahn's algorithm to obtain a topological order
3. Initialize distances array with INF and set dist[s] = 0
4. Relax edges in topological order: for each node u, if dist[u] ≠ INF, update dist[v] = min(dist[v], dist[u] + w) for each outgoing edge (u,v,w)
5. If the topological sort processes fewer than n nodes (indicating a cycle), fall back to Dijkstra's algorithm

For unreachable nodes, distances remain INF, which can be returned as -1 or null as needed.

```javascript
function shortestPath(n, edges, s) {
  // Build graph
  const adj = Array.from({length: n}, () => []);
  const indegree = new Array(n).fill(0);

  for (const [u, v, w] of edges) {
    adj[u].push([v, w]);
    indegree[v]++;
  }

  // Kahn's algorithm for topological sort
  const queue = [];
  for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    if (indegree[i] === 0) queue.push(i);
  }

  const topo = [];
  while (queue.length) {
    const u = queue.shift();
    topo.push(u);
    for (const [v] of adj[u]) {
      if (--indegree[v] === 0) queue.push(v);
    }
  }

  // If cycle detected, use Dijkstra
  if (topo.length < n) {
    return dijkstra(n, edges, s);
  }

  // DP relaxation in topological order
  const INF = Number.MAX_SAFE_INTEGER;
  const dist = new Array(n).fill(INF);
  dist[s] = 0;

  for (const u of topo) {
    if (dist[u] === INF) continue;
    for (const [v, w] of adj[u]) {
      dist[v] = Math.min(dist[v], dist[u] + w);
    }
  }

  return dist;
}
```

Time Complexity: O(n + m) for DAG case, O((n + m) log n) for Dijkstra fallback
Space Complexity: O(n + m)

