- How to adapt for multiple sources and answering many queries efficiently?

## Why This Is Asked
This question tests the ability to extend Dijkstra's algorithm to count shortest paths while handling ties and modular arithmetic—a common pattern in competitive programming and graph algorithms.

## Key Concepts
- Dijkstra's algorithm with path counting augmentation
- Non-negative edge weights, including zero-weight edges
- Modular arithmetic for large path counts and overflow prevention
- Edge case handling: unreachable destinations, multiple optimal paths, zero-weight cycles

## Code Example
```javascript
function countShortestPaths(n, edges, s, t) {
  const MOD = 1e9 + 7;
  const dist = new Array(n).fill(Infinity);
  const ways = new Array(n).fill(0);

  dist[s] = 0;
  ways[s] = 1;

  const pq = new MinPriorityQueue({ priority: x => dist[x] });
  pq.enqueue(s);

  while (!pq.isEmpty()) {
    const u = pq.dequeue().element;

    for (const [v, w] of edges[u]) {
      if (dist[u] + w < dist[v]) {
        dist[v] = dist[u] + w;
        ways[v] = ways[u];
        pq.enqueue(v);
      } else if (dist[u] + w === dist[v]) {
        ways[v] = (ways[v] + ways[u]) % MOD;
      }
    }
  }

  return { distance: dist[t] === Infinity ? -1 : dist[t], paths: ways[t] };
}
