## Key Concepts
**BFS (Breadth-First Search)**: Uses queue, explores neighbors level-by-level. Time: O(V+E). Space: O(V) worst case (all nodes in queue). Guarantees shortest path in unweighted graphs.

**DFS (Depth-First Search)**: Uses stack or recursion, explores as deep as possible before backtracking. Time: O(V+E). Space: O(h) where h is maximum depth (recursion stack), O(V) worst case for skewed graphs.

## When to Use Each
**BFS**: Shortest path routing, social network friend suggestions, web crawlers finding closest pages, level-order tree traversals.

**DFS**: Topological sorting, cycle detection, maze solving, finding connected components, backtracking problems like Sudoku or N-Queens.

## Code Example
```javascript
// BFS - finds shortest path
function bfs(graph, start) {
  const queue = [start];
  const visited = new Set([start]);
  const distances = { [start]: 0 };

  while (queue.length) {
    const node = queue.shift();
    for (const neighbor of graph[node]) {
      if (!visited.has(neighbor)) {
        visited.add(neighbor);
        distances[neighbor] = distances[node] + 1;
        queue.push(neighbor);
      }
    }
  }
  return distances;
}

// DFS - recursive implementation
function dfs(graph, node, visited = new Set(), result = []) {
  if (visited.has(node)) return result;

  visited.add(node);
  result.push(node);

  for (const neighbor of graph[node]) {
    dfs(graph, neighbor, visited, result);
  }

  return result;
}

// DFS - iterative implementation
function dfsIterative(graph, start) {
  const stack = [start];
  const visited = new Set();
  const result = [];

  while (stack.length) {
    const node = stack.pop();
    if (visited.has(node)) continue;

    visited.add(node);
    result.push(node);

    // Add neighbors to stack (reverse for consistent order)
    for (let i = graph[node].length - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
      const neighbor = graph[node][i];
      if (!visited.has(neighbor)) {
        stack.push(neighbor);
      }
    }
  }
  return result;
}
```

## Memory Considerations
BFS can consume significant memory for wide graphs (queue holds all nodes at current level). DFS is memory-efficient for deep, narrow graphs but may cause stack overflow for very deep recursion. Choose based on graph structure and problem requirements.

