## Why This Is Asked

Duplicate values are common in real-world data sets. Traditional 2-way quicksort performs poorly with many duplicates, leading to unnecessary comparisons and degraded performance. 3-way partitioning addresses this by grouping equal elements together, significantly reducing the algorithm's work.

## Key Concepts

- **3-way partitioning (Dutch national flag algorithm)**: Separates array into < pivot, == pivot, and > pivot regions
- **Randomized pivot selection**: Prevents worst-case O(n²) scenarios on already sorted or adversarial input
- **In-place sorting**: Operates with O(1) additional space, using only O(log n) expected stack depth
- **Performance optimization**: Reduces comparisons from O(n log n) to O(n) when many duplicates exist

## Code Example

```javascript
function quicksort3(a, lo = 0, hi = a.length - 1) {
  if (lo >= hi) return;

  // Random pivot selection
  const pivot = a[Math.floor(Math.random() * (hi - lo + 1)) + lo];
  let lt = lo, i = lo, gt = hi;

  // 3-way partitioning
  while (i <= gt) {
    if (a[i] < pivot) {
      [a[lt], a[i]] = [a[i], a[lt]];
      lt++;
      i++;
    } else if (a[i] > pivot) {
      [a[i], a[gt]] = [a[gt], a[i]];
      gt--;
    } else {
      i++; // a[i] === pivot
    }
  }

  // Recursively sort subarrays
  quicksort3(a, lo, lt - 1);
  quicksort3(a, gt + 1, hi);
}
```

## Partitioning Strategy

The algorithm maintains three regions during partitioning:
- `[lo, lt-1]`: elements < pivot
- `[lt, gt]`: elements === pivot (being processed)
- `[gt+1, hi]`: elements > pivot

As we iterate, elements are swapped into their appropriate region, with equal elements naturally forming the middle section that needs no further processing.

