## Why This Is Asked
Autocomplete for large vocabularies is common; a Trie yields fast prefix queries and ordered counts.

## Key Concepts
- Trie vs BST for prefix-based lookup
- DFS with pruning and max-heap to collect top-k results
- Memory optimizations: sparse maps, compact nodes

## Code Example
```javascript
class TrieNode {
  constructor() {
    this.next = new Map();
    this.word = null;
    this.freq = 0;
  }
}

class Trie {
  constructor() {
    this.root = new TrieNode();
  }

  insert(word, delta) {
    let cur = this.root;
    for (const ch of word) {
      if (!cur.next.has(ch)) {
        cur.next.set(ch, new TrieNode());
      }
      cur = cur.next.get(ch);
    }
    cur.word = word;
    cur.freq += delta;
  }

  search(word) {
    let cur = this.root;
    for (const ch of word) {
      if (!cur.next.has(ch)) return false;
      cur = cur.next.get(ch);
    }
    return cur.word === word;
  }

  prefixTop(prefix, k) {
    let cur = this.root;
    for (const ch of prefix) {
      if (!cur.next.has(ch)) return [];
      cur = cur.next.get(ch);
    }

    const results = [];
    const dfs = (node) => {
      if (node.word) {
        results.push({ word: node.word, freq: node.freq });
        if (results.length > k) {
          results.sort((a, b) => b.freq - a.freq);
          results.pop();
        }
      }
      for (const child of node.next.values()) {
        dfs(child);
      }
    };

    dfs(cur);
    return results.sort((a, b) => b.freq - a.freq).slice(0, k).map(r => r.word);
  }
}
```

## Time/Space Trade-offs vs BST/AVL
- **Trie**: O(m) insert/search where m = word length, independent of vocabulary size. Prefix queries O(m + k) where k = results. Space O(α×m) where α = alphabet size.
- **BST/AVL**: O(log n) operations where n = vocabulary size. Prefix queries require O(n) traversal. Space O(n).
- **Trie advantage**: Constant-time prefix lookups, natural ordering by frequency, better cache locality for common prefixes.
- **BST advantage**: More memory efficient for sparse vocabularies, simpler implementation.

## Memory-heavy Vocabulary Justification
For large vocabularies, use:
- **Sparse maps** (Map/Object) instead of fixed arrays for children
- **Node compression** (radix/patricia tries) to merge common prefixes
- **Frequency-based pruning** to remove low-frequency words
- **External storage** for very large datasets, keeping hot prefixes in memory

Tries excel when prefix queries dominate and memory can be optimized through compression techniques.

